# Module 8 – Project 1: Financial Report Redesign

> Part of the [DIO Power BI Analyst Bootcamp](https://www.dio.me/)

---

## Overview

This project takes the financial sales report built in Module 5 and rebuilds it with a focus on user experience — applying principles of positioning, contrast, proportion, and data segmentation to create something that feels intentional rather than just functional.

The brief said there are no rigid rules. So I didn't follow them rigidly.

---

## Design decisions

The original report was clean but generic — the kind of blue corporate dashboard you've seen a hundred times. I wanted something that would actually stop someone scrolling through a portfolio.

The palette runs from deep purple (`#1B0B2E`) through to fuchsia (`#E91E8C`) and deep pink (`#C2185B`). It's not a typical financial report color scheme, which is exactly the point. The UX principle at play: contrast and distinctiveness help users orient themselves and remember what they saw.

Positioning-wise, the KPI cards stay at the top — they're the first question any stakeholder asks ("what are the numbers?"). The time series sits below because it answers the second question ("how did we get here?"). The breakdowns by segment, product, and country sit at the bottom for users who want to dig deeper.

Navigation buttons connect all three pages so the report flows like a document, not a collection of disconnected slides.

---

## Pages

**Page 1 — Sales Report**
Overview of total sales performance. KPI cards, monthly trend, breakdown by segment, product, and country. Date slicer for filtering by period. Visual toggles between chart types (bar/pie, map/treemap).

**Page 2 — Detailed Profit Report**
Profit deep dive with year and country slicers. Waterfall chart showing quarterly profit progression. Line chart by product. Treemap by country.

**Page 3 — Not all sales are equal**
This page was entirely my own addition, not part of the original template. One chart, one insight: Gross Sales vs Profit by Product side by side. Paseo dominates gross sales but the profit margin tells a different story. The gap between those two bars is the most interesting thing in this dataset.

